---
import BlogLayout from '../../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
const faq = [
  { q: `How many verb groups are there in Japanese?`, a: `Three groups: Group 1 (五段 godan / u-verbs) includes most verbs ending in a consonant+u sound. Group 2 (一段 ichidan / ru-verbs) includes verbs ending in -iru or -eru. Group 3 (irregular) has only two verbs: する (to do) and 来る (to come). About 75% of common verbs are Group 1, 20% Group 2, and 5% are する-compounds.` },
  { q: `What is the te-form used for?`, a: `Te-form is arguably the most versatile conjugation in Japanese. It is used for: requests (食べてください — please eat), connecting sequential actions (食べて飲んで — eat and drink), progressive tense (食べている — is eating), permission (食べてもいい — may I eat), and giving/receiving favors (食べてあげる — eat for someone). Mastering te-form unlocks dozens of grammar patterns.` },
  { q: `Should I learn polite form or casual form first?`, a: `Start with polite form (ます/です). It is appropriate in nearly all situations — with strangers, at work, in stores. Using casual form incorrectly can be rude. Once comfortable with polite form, learn casual form for conversations with friends. Most textbooks (Genki, Minna no Nihongo) teach polite form first for this reason.` },
  { q: `How do I know if a verb is Group 1 or Group 2?`, a: `If the verb ends in -iru or -eru, it is likely Group 2 (食べる, 見る, 寝る). All other -u endings are Group 1 (飲む, 書く, 話す). However, some -iru/-eru verbs are actually Group 1 (帰る, 走る, 切る) — these exceptions must be memorized. When in doubt, check a dictionary or use our Verb Conjugator tool.` },
  { q: `Is Japanese verb conjugation harder than other languages?`, a: `In some ways, Japanese is easier: verbs do not change based on the subject (I eat, you eat, he eats are all 食べる). There is no grammatical gender affecting verbs. The main challenge is the number of forms (polite, casual, te-form, potential, passive, causative) and the Group 1 consonant changes. With systematic study, most learners find it manageable within 3-6 months.` }
];
const relatedTools = [
  { name: "Verb Conjugator", url: "/japanese/tools/verb-conjugator/" },
  { name: "Particle Guide", url: "/japanese/tools/particle-guide/" },
  { name: "JLPT Vocabulary", url: "/japanese/tools/jlpt-vocabulary/" }
];
const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: "three-groups", text: "The Three Verb Groups Explained" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "polite-form", text: "Polite Form (ます masu)" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "negative", text: "Negative Form (ない nai)" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "past-tense", text: "Past Tense (た ta / ました mashita)" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "te-form", text: "Te-Form: The Swiss Army Knife of Japanese" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "potential", text: "Potential Form: Expressing Ability" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "conjugation-chart", text: "Complete Conjugation Chart" },
